AB  - Because subjective probability assessments do not represent measurements of empirical quantities, they often exhibit vagueness, or ambiguity [1]. We adopt a standard approach to modeling vagueness as a second-order probability (SOP) on a first-order probability. We define the expected value of including vagueness (EVIV) as the change in expected value due to explicit probabilistic representation of vagueness. We show that, under general conditions, the EVIV is always zero, regardless of the SOP or the loss or utility function. Although not surprising, this result shows that representing higher-order uncertainty as SOP never changes the output of a decision model. We analyze the value of reducing vagueness, and we provide a framework for measuring the expected value of reducing vagueness (EVRV) on a probability assessment using equivalent sample size and a new measure, the relative information multiple (RIM). Our approach uses preposterior analysis, conjugate distributions, and sufficient statistics, tools often studied in statistical decision theory [2]. We use influence diagrams [3] to represent the flow of potential but unobserved evidence from a vagueness-reducing activity. We demonstrate our results for a simple decision problem implemented in Demos, a decision modeling software environment. The EVRV is based on modeling vagueness by SOP, and provision of an elicitation method for encoding SOP. It operationalizes the previously vague topic of vagueness by measuring precisely of the value of reducing it; it also provides a bridge to recent psychological work by modeling ambiguity as a consequence of missing information [4] resulting from a lack of competence or expertise [5]. © 1996 IEEE.
